AGI - Since the beginning of the year are four cases of Dengue from import registered in Umbria: three on the territory of competence of the Usl Umbria 1 and one on that of the Usl Umbria 2. Last year they were two. This is what the Health and Public Health Service of the Department of Prevention of Usl Umbria 1, directed by Dr. Igino Fusco Moffa.
&nbsp;
"We are witnessing a global increase in Dengue cases, at the moment particularly at the expense of the Regions of the Americas (4.1 million cases in 2023 and already 5 million from the beginning of 2024) but also in Southeast Asia and in Saharan Africa. They are all areas of work or tourist travel, especially in summer and, consequently, it is plausible to expect an increase in import cases", explains Igino Fusco Moffa.
&nbsp;
"The Dengue - continues - is caused by four very similar viruses (Den-1, Den-2, Den-3 and Den-4) and is transmitted to humans by the mosquito bites of the species Aedes which, in turn, point a infected person. There is no direct contagion between human beings, even if man is the main host of the virus. The virus circulates in the blood of the infected person for 2-7 days and at this time the mosquito may take it and transmit it to others. In Italy and in Umbria the Aedes albopictus is now autochthonous, the so-called zanzara tigre, vector responsible for the transmission of the virus. It is reported that the tiger mosquito is able to transmit also the Zika virus, particularly dangerous for fetal damage in case of infection of pregnant women". &nbsp;
